03:21.505 --> 03:23.290
Hello?

03:23.333 --> 03:25.292
Is anybody home?

03:36.085 --> 03:38.653
[Speaks French]

03:38.696 --> 03:41.395
Philippe Saint-Andre,
is he in?

03:43.962 --> 03:45.312
Do you speak English?

03:45.355 --> 03:47.009
Parlez anglais?

03:56.888 --> 03:59.326
[Speaking French]

04:18.040 --> 04:19.346
[Gun safety clicks]

04:23.306 --> 04:25.874
Quite the pepper gun
you got there, Madame.

04:28.964 --> 04:30.705
Philippe...

04:30.748 --> 04:32.272
Where is he?

04:46.503 --> 04:47.808
[Door slams]

04:47.852 --> 04:49.071
Patrice: I would
consider that one

04:49.114 --> 04:50.812
of Audrey's
warmer welcomes.

04:50.855 --> 04:52.292
But she tells the truth,

04:52.335 --> 04:54.381
I do not think Philippe
has ever married,

04:54.424 --> 04:57.297
and frankly, I do not
know who would marry him.

04:57.340 --> 04:59.037
Sam:
You haven't met Brigid.

04:59.081 --> 05:01.692
Sadly,
I have met many Brigids.

05:01.736 --> 05:03.259
She paid me
a lot of money

05:03.303 --> 05:05.348
to make sure the kid
was handed over to her father.

05:05.392 --> 05:06.871
She wasn't one to
part with money,

05:06.915 --> 05:08.482
much less a lot of it.

05:08.525 --> 05:12.007
So do you know where this
Philippe Saint-Andre is?

05:12.050 --> 05:14.531
Who knows?
Philippe is a vagabond.

05:14.575 --> 05:17.142
Sometimes he's here,
sometimes he's there.

05:17.186 --> 05:19.275
So why the will
instructed you

05:19.319 --> 05:21.233
to bring the girl
here is a mystery.

05:21.277 --> 05:23.279
All I know is I was
sent a plane ticket,

05:23.323 --> 05:26.500
first-class Pan Am to Istanbul,
to pick up the kid,

05:26.543 --> 05:30.025
and two more tickets,
coach this time, to Marseilles.

05:30.068 --> 05:31.548
And then so instructed,

05:31.592 --> 05:33.028
you come all the way
to our little village,

05:33.071 --> 05:34.725
just to knock on a door

05:34.769 --> 05:37.075
and hand over the girl
to whoever answered.

05:37.119 --> 05:38.860
I was told her father
would answer.

05:38.903 --> 05:41.819
You did not wonder if the
child would even be welcome?

05:41.863 --> 05:44.909
I was paid too much
to wonder.

05:44.953 --> 05:46.389
This was strictly
a business matter

05:46.433 --> 05:48.260
between you
and Miss O'Shaughnessy?

05:48.304 --> 05:50.611
She didn't pick my name
out of a hat

05:50.654 --> 05:52.177
if that's
what you're asking.

05:52.221 --> 05:53.701
We knew each other.

05:53.744 --> 05:55.137
I see.

05:55.180 --> 05:56.965
When you say
"knew each other,"

05:57.008 --> 06:00.272
you mean you knew
each other...well.

06:00.316 --> 06:02.492
Well enough
so she trusted me.

06:02.536 --> 06:05.539
You were lovers,
perhaps?

06:05.582 --> 06:07.236
Oh, Jesus, you French.

06:07.279 --> 06:09.369
-So yes?
-Briefly, didn't end well.

06:09.412 --> 06:10.674
They never do.

06:10.718 --> 06:13.024
Hearts break,
one moves on,

06:13.068 --> 06:15.200
the other one becomes
lonely and bitter.

06:15.244 --> 06:16.463
We didn't get that far.

06:16.506 --> 06:18.378
-Why not?
-I put her in jail.

06:20.815 --> 06:22.251
So, this
Brigid O'Shaughnessy,

06:22.294 --> 06:24.645
she trusted you because
you put her in jail.

06:24.688 --> 06:27.648
She trusted me because
I got her out of jail.

06:27.691 --> 06:28.823
Got her out?

06:28.866 --> 06:29.954
How?

06:29.998 --> 06:32.000
I knew who to talk to.

06:32.043 --> 06:34.002
A most useful skill.

06:34.045 --> 06:36.657
And the reason you felt
so compelled to free her?

06:36.700 --> 06:39.007
She was two years
into 20 when she got sick

06:39.050 --> 06:41.662
and found out she was dying,
or so she thought.

06:41.705 --> 06:44.491
Turned out
even her body could lie.

06:44.534 --> 06:47.058
They paroled her and she
lived another four years

06:47.102 --> 06:49.321
before she died
in that train derailment

06:49.365 --> 06:51.236
outside Istanbul
a few months back.

06:51.280 --> 06:54.501
Irony has always been
my favorite form of justice.

06:54.544 --> 06:56.154
Not to mention
the time it saves you.

06:56.198 --> 06:59.854
What was she doing,
may I ask, in Istanbul?

06:59.897 --> 07:01.116
Antiquing.

07:02.900 --> 07:04.249
After her release
from prison,

07:04.293 --> 07:07.078
did you two pick up
were you left off?

07:07.122 --> 07:09.341
It didn't last much
longer than the car ride

07:09.385 --> 07:11.213
from the prison
to the motel.

07:11.256 --> 07:14.434
Then she broke her parole
and lammed off to Europe.

07:14.477 --> 07:17.393
You did not feel
as if no time had passed,

07:17.437 --> 07:19.917
that despite all the
heartbreak and the bitterness,

07:19.961 --> 07:23.834
you could still find
a small ember to reignite?

07:23.878 --> 07:25.227
I have to say, Chief,

07:25.270 --> 07:27.447
you've got a funny
kind of curiosity.

07:27.490 --> 07:29.231
I am a police officer.

07:29.274 --> 07:31.059
I am curious
about everything,

07:31.102 --> 07:34.932
especially about men with guns
looking for trouble

07:34.976 --> 07:36.543
or perhaps that bulge
in your coat

07:36.586 --> 07:38.501
is a lollipop
for the little girl.

07:38.545 --> 07:40.242
I'm looking for someone,
is all.

07:40.284 --> 07:41.635
Then I have mistaken you

07:41.678 --> 07:43.114
for the sort of man
who pays attention.

07:43.158 --> 07:44.768
I couldn't tell you
what sort of man I am,

07:44.812 --> 07:47.336
other than
I keep my promises,

07:47.379 --> 07:49.251
particularly
when I'm paid to.

07:51.427 --> 07:53.603
My advice...

07:53.647 --> 07:56.258
take the child back
to the United States.

07:56.301 --> 07:58.347
If Philippe Saint-Andre
is her father,

07:58.390 --> 07:59.914
she's better off
an orphan.

07:59.957 --> 08:01.959
All the same,
I need to find him.

08:02.003 --> 08:06.050
And all the same,
I am suggesting, politely,

08:06.094 --> 08:07.574
you look elsewhere.

08:10.054 --> 08:12.883
[Vehicle hums]

08:12.927 --> 08:15.582
[Footsteps echo]

08:20.891 --> 08:21.979
[Car door closes]

08:22.023 --> 08:24.242
[Speaks French]

08:24.286 --> 08:25.505
Samuel Spade.

08:29.030 --> 08:31.554
